title: Grateful Dead Live at Nassau Coliseum on 1980-05-14
lineage: Master Soundboard Cassette > Reel to Reel > DAT > CDR
description: Alabama Getaway-> Promised Land, Candyman, Mexicali Blues-> El Paso, Tennessee Jed, Let It Grow-> Althea, Easy To Love You-> The Music Never Stopped Feel Like A Stranger-> Sugaree, Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Comes A Time-> The Other One-> Drums-> Black Peter-> Around & Around-> Johnny B. Goode, E: Don't Ease Me In

reviews.review_text: This was not the pick of the litter I was at Friday and that really rocked - comes a time> other one was cool but for the most part this is slow and trippy - tight and listenable - parts of this are on go to nassau

Go To Nassau None of this show was used for Go To Nassau. I was at this show, felt it was kinda laid back, but fun. I agree that the 3rd night of the run was the best by far.

comes a time very heart felt version of Comes a Time. I've always like the Strangers from this decade as well.
comes a time now i was never at any dead shows but damn jerry was just burnin my ears of on that comes a time, i would say this is a much better version then the sun dome.

let it grow into althea this blend of Let It Grow into Althea is so amazing.  i wish they did it more and also that this recorded version didn't cut right as they blend into each other.  love the Easy To Love, too.  and if this wasn't a great night for you who were there, you are spoiled!  :-)also, amazed you remember the shows so vividly!  that was near 30 years ago, and you speak as if it was yesterday!
My 3rd show I've always loved this show, mainly The Music Never Stopped and Sugaree. They were on fire!!!

Very strong show This is a very good sounding show, and it has some very good playing. Particularly the Sailor->Saint and the Let It Grow. Worth the download.

The Lawn Giland base
The lesser of a 3-day run that gets better with each set. These shows were before the hot Boulder and Anchorage shows (parts of the next two nights are on Go to Nassau). They were making an effort to promote Go to Heaven, which was just hitting stores, and this night played 7 of the 8 (live) songs from the album! First Set. Alabama is trying for none better the next night. Jer uses "just turn round" here (and sit down), showing he was testing comprehension over scanning. The 16th is better for Promised Land and etc., for a just-a-little-below-average set. The mid-set Let it Grow is nice - they were usually playing it into Deal at the time. Easy to Love You was only played one day of the run - probably because this almost trainwrecks. Second Set. Brent's great on Feel Like a Stranger, but the next night's the one. Sugaree is long but a bit aimless. The 16th is better for the next couple, though Saint has a cool little jam-after. The drummers stay for Space for most dates on this tour. Around and Around is better on this night. Johnny B. Goode is the tightest they play all night, culminating in a hot Dough Knees - leave 'em thinking you were great! 1st Set:   C- 2nd Set: C Overall = 2½ stars Highlights: Don't Ease Me In - There are some great ones in '80. Some are even this good. SOURCES: Clugston SBD is best for the 2nd set. The dusborne matrix is better for the 1st set, where the vox are mixed too high, and for the AUD-only encore. However, it's pitched too slow starting at Tennessee Jed, needing +1%.
